      <page>
        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <title>Dirty Tricks, part I</title>

          <introduction>
            <p>
              We will use integration by parts twice to find <m>\int e^{-2x}\sin 3x\,dx</m>.
            </p>
          </introduction>


          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                First use <m>u = \sin 3x</m>, <m>dv = e^{-2x}\,dx</m>.
                The result should contain another integral suitable for integration by parts.
              </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
              <p>
                Let <m>u=\sin(3x)</m>, <m>dv = e^{-2x}\,dx</m>.
                Then <m>du = 3\cos(3x)\,dx</m> and <m>v = -\frac12e^{-2x}</m>.
                So
                <me>
                  \begin{aligned} I &amp;= -\frac{1}{2}e^{-2x}\sin(3x) + \frac32 \int e^{-2x} \cos(3x)\,dx \\ \end{aligned}
                </me>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>


          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Find the remaining integral by parts using <m>dv = \cos 3x\,dx</m> (or some constant multiple of <m>\cos 3x</m>).
                What happens?
              </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
              <p>
                If <m>dv = \cos 3x\,dx</m>, then <m>u = e^{-2x}</m>.
                So <m>v = \frac13 \sin 3x</m> and <m>du = -2 e^{-2x}\,dx</m>.
                Thus
                <me>
                  \int e^{-2x} \cos(3x)\,dx = \frac13 e^{-2x}\sin 3x + \frac23 \int e^{-2x}\sin 3x\,dx
                </me>
                Putting this together with the first part gives
                <me>
                  \begin{split} \int e^{-2x}\sin 3x\,dx &amp;= -\frac{1}{2}e^{-2x}\sin(3x) + \frac32 \int e^{-2x} \cos(3x)\,dx \\ &amp;= -\frac{1}{2}e^{-2x}\sin(3x) + \frac32 \left\{\frac13 e^{-2x}\sin 3x + \frac23 \int e^{-2x}\sin 3x\,dx\right\} \\ &amp;= \int e^{-2x}\sin 3x\,dx \end{split}
                </me>
                We have come exactly full circle, and the reason why is that our second integration by parts undid the first one.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>


          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Try the same thing now with <m>u = \cos 3x</m>.
                What happens now?
              </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
              <p>
                This time,
                <me>
                  \int e^{-2x}\sin 3x\,dx = -\frac12 e^{-2x} \cos (3x) -\frac32 \int e^{-2x} \sin(3x)\,dx
                </me>
                so
                <me>
                  \begin{aligned} \int e^{-2x}\sin 3x\,dx &amp;= -\frac{1}{2}e^{-2x}\sin(3x) + \frac32\left\{ -\frac12 e^{-2x} \cos (3x) -\frac32 \int e^{-2x} \sin(3x)\,dx \right\} \\ &amp;= -\frac{1}{2}e^{-2x}\sin(3x) - \frac34 e^{-2x} \cos(3x) -\frac{9}{4} \int e^{-2x}\sin 3x\,dx \\ \end{aligned}
                </me>
                We are back where we started, but in a good way.
                <me>
                  \begin{aligned} \frac{13}{4} \int e^{-2x}\sin 3x\,dx &amp;= -\frac{1}{2}e^{-2x}\sin(3x) - \frac34 e^{-2x} \cos(3x) +C\\ \implies \int e^{-2x}\sin 3x\,dx &amp;= -\frac{2}{13}e^{-2x}\sin(3x) - \frac{3}{13} e^{-2x} \cos(3x)+C \end{aligned}
                </me>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
        </exercise>
      </page>


